Review: I've been hesitant to get a digital frame because the setup and ongoing maintenance sounded exhausting. This was pretty out the box and easy to use, thankfully.Pros:- The picture quality is great, and nothing is pixelated long as your photos are at least 1200x1800 (but even then, I've got old photos that still show up well)- Option to fit to frame or original size if they're cropped is nice, and the background adjusts to blurred behind it- The frame auto orients to portrait or landscape depending on how you want to stand it up- Sleep function so it turns off during night hours is great to reduce light pollution- Option to display clock in 12 or 24hr format- Slot for USD stick or SD card if you want to keep local storage of photos instead of storing in the cloud on the app.Cons:- The app takes some getting used to. It can only upload 8-9 photos at a time, otherwise it prompts you to bilk upload (but then you can't edit each size manually). First time I did a bulk upload, it picked up other photos I did not select, so, not sure what's going on there.- My hesitancy with using any tech that has an app (especially from a 3rd party and not a major known brand) is that it's likely to fall into disuse, the developers will probably stop updating it eventually, and it will be obsolete. I'm glad there's local storage on it to address when that will eventually probably happen, and this wasn't expensive, so not an immediate issue, but something to keep in mind for any device that comes with a propietary app.

I bought one first just to see if the quality of the frame and display are good. It turns out that the the quality is much better than my expectation. The frame arrived in a nice box and the display has high resolution and the color dynamic is also great. I can display pictures and videos all from my cell phone (remotely). It is also easy to set up. Furthermore, it is inexpensive. I am very satisfied with the product. Really nicely made. I immediately bought two more for other rooms in my house.

This frame looks really nice and does a good job trying to look like a traditional wooden frame. I do like that this particular frame has worked well so far. The picture quality is good but it also depends on the quality of the photo. It does not do anything too crazy in terms of enhancing the picture quality so be aware of that. Regardless of that, I do like this digital photo frame. You are able to rotate it as needed. It does not have the traditional frame holder that pops out of the back. It is just a simple screw on plastic piece. The angle cannot be adjusted unfortunately. You are able to mount this on a desktop monitor mount which is interesting. There are also holds to mount this on the wall as needed. You just need to be aware that this device does not come with a hanging aid so it can be hard to mount for some. There is internal memory and I do love that you are able to transmit the picture to easily share the photo directly from your phone as needed. You are also able to install a USB flash drive or an SD card if you want more memory but you are allocated 32 gb of memory as needed. I am able to share easily all my current photos in one picture frame and just have it rotate through different pictures to show all my different pictures. I got this because I am limited on space in my home so I cannot have a bunch of photos frames so this is something that could show all my pictures family and travels. In terms of feel, the photo frame tries to mimic the wood like finish but it is a solid plastic frame from what I can tell. It has a smoother feel. The color is pretty dark so it is not really that great for the brighter rooms. The frame is pretty strong so it should not break very easily. The paint is put on well so you do not have to worry about any flaking or chipping. The screen is pretty sturdy. I am unsure if it is temper glass or strong plastic but it is responsive. The responsiveness of the screen. I am wondering why it utilize a monitor mount style hole in order to mount a certain way. It does come with a screen cover you need to remove. It runs a very simple to use operating system so you do not have to worry about not being able to use it. It can play all the pictures you want but the thing you need to make sure is that the pictures are same resolution and such. For the most part, it is pretty much plug any play. It can read an SD card. It does not have to be formatted from what I can tell.  It does come with a power outlet and I did not try to see if this can run on a portable battery but it is harder to hide the cable if you are hanging this on your wall. The transition between photos seem to move pretty fluently through. It does not get warm. Overall this is a decent smart photo frame to have. The wood looks good for the rustic decorum and it is well painted / made frame. It tries to mimic the photo frame as best they can. The touch screen is nice. The application could be better though.

I received this digital frame as a gift and I have truly enjoyed it!  It is a nice size to be able to see your photos from anywhere in the room. The app was very easy to figure out and easy to upload pictures. Ample storage so it holds many photos. The black wood frame looks expensive and would fit any décor nicely. I have used the frame for many months now and have not had any problems. I plan to give this frame as gifts for this upcoming holiday season!

The frame is a nice size, visible to everyone from across the room.Software is responsive and intuitive.Our whole family enjoys the photos.One issue - the app doesn't allow me to upload photos from Google Photos, only Samsung gallery. Also, even though the frame is connected to the WiFi, I cannot sent photos to it from my home computer.App also doesn't support Amazon photos, which is inconvenient as well.The only way for me to upload photos is to copy them on a flash drive and then import from the flash drive.If they fix the app to allow import directly into the frame via WiFi, I would change the rating to 5 stars.

I wanted to buy another laptop for work purposes but also be useful for travelling and for gaming so I saw this laptop for sale during Black Friday! Excellent purchase! Here is my pros and cons after a week of owning this:Con:1. 1920 x 1200 FHD 165Hz Display is very much an downgrade against my Legion 5 Pro 16" 2560 x 1600 IPS LCD 165Hz Display... But I guess with the parts offered, ASUS had to make some budget cuts somewhere I guess... (for the model I've chosen and not wanting to spend more than $1500 USD).2. Automatic MUX Switching is annoying... it optimizes which option to best suit for your current usage at the time (e.g. if you ran an game vs closing the game and brings you to the desktop). The automatic switch seems like its great and all but it ruins the display setting and when an game is playing, it switches again and sends you back to the desktop and ruins the display setting/resolution once more... Its best to just set it on the dedicated GPU option so you dont have to deal with this...3. Standard SSD Capacity is too low (again with cost saving measures but literally everyone these days just buy additional SSD stick anyways)... so snagged an SK.Hynix P41 SSD 2TB stick on sale to manually install for loading heavy application and games on there; really easy to install and easy to unscrew the back; there is an empty NVMe Gen4 M.2 2280 slot for you to install your SSDWorks Great after installing correctly and no Issues now! (make sure after install of SSD, just load into Windows and open up disk management to reformat (quick format! never full on SSD!) No need to tinker with BIOS setting...Do not tighten the SSD screws too much where the stick bends! thats incorrect! screw in ever so slightly so that the stick itself wont lodge out or move at all.Pros:1. RTX 4060 8GB - 140W Max TGP2. i7-13650HX - beats my Ryzen-7 5800H on my Legion 5 Pro3. RGB bar looks awesome!4. Battery 90WhNeutral:1. RGB Keys - heard mixed reviews on ASUS's design on this; of course, the Legion 5 RGB keyboard design is the best of the best but this is just okay and its not too bad in my eyes.2. Same weight and nearly the same dimensions as my Legion 5 Pro so portability is the same-ish but way better than my old MSI gaming laptop from 2017 where you can put this in your backpack and still have room to put other accessories and such.This is all I've noticed currently but either way, its a great mid-tier gaming laptop! I can run cyberpunk all max setting without issues or framerate drops and every other AAA game titles up to this point... This laptop should last an long time until AAA games becomes more graphically intense and requiring more processing power... but again this is the best you can get for your money and highly recommend!

Wow! I was a little hesitant to pull the trigger because of some of the reviewers on here saying they got a terrible renewed iPad... I can assure you that the one that I received was in overall 4.5/5 condition. The screen looked brand new, and even the rest of the body didn't appear to have any sort of defects. The cellular connection I'm getting (Ting Mobile, baby) is as steady as my cell phone (I was a little worried that the cell antenna in these wouldn't be of great quality, but I'm happy to say it is.)I've never owned any iPads, but recently got an iPhone and chose this over other tablets because I know Apple retina displays are actually very nice. Colors come across as vivid. Resolution turned up to the point where you're really struggling to make out individual pixels, and the screen is bright enough that I'm not struggling to see this in the car. And I bought this because I wanted a nice, big screen to look at when I'm in the car. One note about the display - it's a 4:3 display rather than the more contemporary 16:9 displays of the Android tablet world. That makes this about a ~9"-9.3" display when watching content with a 1.777:1 or 1.85:1 aspect ratio which are the standard aspect ratios for films/TV shows (which is why your TV at home is a 16:9 aspect ratio!) Back to car use, the GPS works very well alongside cellular data. There are some cool navigation apps available on Apple, plus now I don't feel left out when there's other neat apps for Apple that I can't get on my Android phone. Also there are actually so many good accessories available for this thing because Apple has a small product line in comparison to the dozens of Android tablets and phones coming out each year from numerous manufacturers which equals lots of accessories with not so many reviews.I chose this specific model because it's the newest cellular Apple tablet at this price point. As of now, it's about 2-3 years old. The other ones I found on Amazon around the $200-300 range were as old as 8 years and without cellular, which is why I spent the extra money for something like this. I am happier than I was when I made my impulse buy which is impressive. You really do get a lot of tech for the money. A new 64gb iPad 10.2 with cellular is $459. This is only 32gb, and with a fresh install of iOS you get 23gb available to you. A little worried it won't be enough for me, but I'll probably manage.My only con so far is that the battery had a weird glitch. When you're in a high state of charge, it seems to be discharging at a slow enough rate. I got down to around 40% after using it for about 4 hours after using it to stream Hulu using cell data with full brightness. Then while using it with GPS on and streaming Spotify with full brightness on, it jumped from about 35% down to 20% within a few minutes. I can't complain too much because this is a 3 year old device about 2/3rds the price of new.I got mine from the seller "techexchangee" - came with a 5v/2.4a charger (or 12 watt) charger plus cable. Shipped in a plain box with lots of bubble wrap. Again, from the outside, I wouldn't have been able to tell it was renewed.P.S. On Amazon, I found a tablet mount for a car using a CD player and that thing is great. Highly recommend that if you want to use this in a car. It's the "APPS2CAR universal car mount CD slot" for $20.

It's a Game Drive that can work on Xbox, PC and PlayStation.  I'm currently using for my PS5 that's shown in the picture.  The drive itself is very light weight.  I would make sure you give it plenty of space by your game console.  The cord it comes with is a Micro USB 3.0 and it is a good wire but it is short.  Transfer speed is great and it is fast.  Downloading the games from the Internet took me the whole day just to put on the drive but I was ok with that because I did have a big list of games that I wanted to put on this drive.  Do note that this only works for only Xbox One / PS4 games only, don't expect PS5 or Series X games to go on here.  It does feel very reliable, it does heat a bit when downloading or running games but it's not to the level of Overheating.  It is very easy to use and the connection is very fast.  You are using USB 3.0 with the next gen feature on it to make it run fast.  I have not experience any data losses on it so it seems very promising.  Overall I would recommend picking this one up and it is very promising.  It does come with Xbox Game Pass Ultimate for one month so that is a nice bonus.  Always make sure to register your product to Seagate to get that warranty if something does go wrong.  Anyways that's it, it's a decent Game drive.
